sols_latex:
First, note that

\begin{align*}
-\sin\left(\frac1{n}\right) \leq (-1)^n \sin\left(\frac1{n}\right) \leq \sin\left(\frac1{n}\right)
\end{align*}

Further, since

\begin{align*}
\lim_{n \to \infty} \frac1{n} = 0
\end{align*}

and $\displaystyle \sin x$ is continuous at 0,

\begin{align*}
\lim_{n \to \infty} \sin\left(\frac1{n}\right) = \sin\left(\lim_{n \to \infty} \frac1{n}\right) = \sin(0) = 0
\end{align*}

Similarly,

\begin{align*}
\lim_{n \to \infty} -\sin\left(\frac1{n}\right) = -0 = 0.
\end{align*}

By the squeeze theorem,

\begin{align*}
\lim_{n \to \infty} (-1)^n \sin\left(\frac1{n}\right)
\end{align*}

exists and equals 0 as well.

The alternating series test says that

\begin{align*}
\sum_{n=1}^\infty (-1)^n a_n
\end{align*}

converges if \emph{a\textsubscript{n}} is monotonically decreasing. In
our case, $a_n = \sin\left(\frac1{n}\right)$, and since $\frac1{n}$
monotonically decreases as \emph{n} increases, and \emph{sin(x)} is a
monotone function for \emph{x} in \emph{{[}0,1{]}} we find that indeed
$a_n = \sin\left(\frac1{n}\right)$ is monotonically decreasing. Hence

\begin{align*}
\sum_{n=1}^\infty (-1)^n a_n
\end{align*}

converges. But the question didn't ask if the series converges, but if
the sequence \emph{\{(-1)\textsuperscript{n} a\textsubscript{n}\}}
converges. This, however, follow as well because if a series
$\sum_{n=1}^\infty b_n$ converges, then the sequence
\emph{\{b\textsubscript{n}\}} must converge to zero, that is

\begin{align*}
0 = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} b_n = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} (-1)^n \sin\left(\frac1{n}\right)
\end{align*}

Hence, $(-1)^n \sin\left(\frac1{n}\right)$ converges to \emph{0}.

